<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,258,1327]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,366,391]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[513,726,366,391]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="expressa">
<emphasis box="[513,726,366,391]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Stigmella expressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. The combination of long vinculum with large lateral lobes, gnathos with two sleder processes, two large apical processes of valva, transtilla with long sublateral processes, and two large cornuti in the male genitalia distinguishes 
<taxonomicName box="[908,1007,438,463]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lepida" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[908,1007,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">S. lepida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1014,1104,438,463]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1014,1104,438,463]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[1273,1378,438,463]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1273,1378,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Stigmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The host-plant 
<taxonomicName box="[270,501,474,499]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aronioides">
<emphasis box="[270,501,474,499]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Acalypha aronioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also make this species distinctive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,258,1327]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,510,535]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[277,364,510,535]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,193,1809]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 35. Adults of the central Andean Nepticulidae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557165/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
). Forewing length about 
<quantity box="[653,744,510,535]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
; wingspan 
<quantity box="[874,1015,510,535]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.75" metricValueMax="5.8" metricValueMin="5.7" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="5.75" valueMax="5.8" valueMin="5.7">5.7–5.8 mm</quantity>
. Head: palpi grey cream; frontal tuft fuscous brown to beige on frons; collor yellowish cream; scape yellowish cream with some pale brown and brown scales; antenna slightly longer than half the length of forewing; flagellum with 29–30 segments, grey-brown with some purple iridescence on upper side, greyish cream on underside. Thorax, tegula and forewing golden cream irregularly speckled with brown to black-brown scales; fringe greyish cream to grey; underside of forewing dark grey-brown, without spots or androconia. Hindwing pale grey-brown to grey with light purple iridescence on upper side and underside, without spots or androconia; its fringe pale grey-brown to grey. Legs grey to dark grey on upper side, brownish cream on underside. Abdomen fuscous with strong purple iridescence on upper side, greyish cream to cream on underside; genital plates greyish cream to cream; anal tufts very short, indistinctive, greyish cream.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,258,1327]" box="[199,418,834,859]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,834,859]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Female</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,258,1327]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,370,870,895]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[384,516,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURES 55 – 60" captionStartId="26.[151,264,1978,2001]" captionTargetBox="[163,1433,198,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[153,1433,195,1957]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 55 – 60. Male genitalia of Stigmella lepida Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. AD 724 (ZMUC); 55, 56, phallus; 57 – 59, capsule with phallus removed; 60, valva." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557171/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs 55–60</figureCitation>
). Capsule much longer (260 µm) than wide (150 µm). Vinculum with long ventral plate and large lateral lobes. Uncus with four small lobes. Gnathos with two caudal processes and angular plate. Valva 130–135 µm long, 50–60 µm wide, with two very large apical processes and slightly bulged inner lobe; transtilla with very long sublateral processes. Juxta membranous, indistinctive. Phallus (
<figureCitation box="[1142,1270,978,1003]" captionStart="FIGURES 55 – 60" captionStartId="26.[151,264,1978,2001]" captionTargetBox="[163,1433,198,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[153,1433,195,1957]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 55 – 60. Male genitalia of Stigmella lepida Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. AD 724 (ZMUC); 55, 56, phallus; 57 – 59, capsule with phallus removed; 60, valva." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557171/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs 55, 56</figureCitation>
) 265 µm long, 55–70 µm wide; vesica with two large cornuti.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,258,1327]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,330,1050,1075]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Bionomics.</emphasis>
Host-plant: 
<taxonomicName authority="Pax &amp; K. Hoffm." authorityName="Pax &amp; K. Hoffm." box="[470,903,1050,1075]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aronioides">
<emphasis box="[470,702,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Acalypha aronioides</emphasis>
Pax &amp; K. Hoffm.
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[917,1073,1050,1075]" captionStart="FIGURES 111 – 115" captionStartId="62.[151,264,1804,1827]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,201,1775]" captionTargetId="figure@62.[151,1436,193,1783]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 111 – 115. Leaf-mines of Stigmella acalyphae Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., and S. lepida Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. on Acalypha L. 111, 112, host-plant, Acalypha aronioides Pax &amp; K. Hoffm.; 113 – 115, leaf-mines (Note: leaf-mines of these two species are similar and were mixed up during fieldwork)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557187/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs 111, 112</figureCitation>
). Larvae mine leaves in October (together with other species— 
<taxonomicName authority="Diskus &amp; Stonis" authorityName="Diskus &amp; Stonis" box="[489,826,1086,1111]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acalyphae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[489,632,1086,1111]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">S. acalyphae</emphasis>
Diškus &amp; Stonis
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[837,927,1086,1111]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[837,927,1086,1111]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). Leaf-mines of these two species are similar and, therefore, were mixed up during the fieldwork (
<figureCitation box="[775,936,1122,1147]" captionStart="FIGURES 111 – 115" captionStartId="62.[151,264,1804,1827]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,201,1775]" captionTargetId="figure@62.[151,1436,193,1783]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 111 – 115. Leaf-mines of Stigmella acalyphae Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., and S. lepida Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. on Acalypha L. 111, 112, host-plant, Acalypha aronioides Pax &amp; K. Hoffm.; 113 – 115, leaf-mines (Note: leaf-mines of these two species are similar and were mixed up during fieldwork)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/557187/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs 113–115</figureCitation>
). Adults emerged in November. Otherwise biology unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
